In 2012, the color of the year, Tangerine Tango, was used to create a [[cosmetics|makeup]] line, in partnership with [[Sephora]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.psfk.com/2012/03/pantone-sephora.html | title=Pantone Teams Up With Sephora to Create A Color-Saturated Makeup Line | first=Emma| last= Hutchings| work = PSFK | date= 2012-03-23 | accessdate= March 23, 2012}}</ref> The product line, named Sephora + Pantone Universe collection, features Tangerine Tango–embellished false lashes; nail lacquers, cream, glitters, and high-pigment lip glosses.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.vogue.com/vogue-daily/article/orange-crush-sephora-and-pantone-team-up-for-an-nyc-pop-up-shop/ | title= Orange Crush: Sephora and Pantone Team Up for an NYC Pop-Up Shop | first =Ana| last=Sragovic| work = [[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]| date=2012-03-21| accessdate =March 23, 2012}}</ref>

The person behind Pantone's Color of the Year, Executive Director of the Pantone Color Institute [[Leatrice Eiseman]], explains in an interview how 2014's Color of the Year, Radiant Orchid, was chosen:
{{Quote | I look for ascending color trends, colors that are being used in broader ways and broader context than before...  In this case, Radiant Orchid descends from the purple family, which is kind of a magical color that denotes creativity and innovation. Purple is just that kind of a complex, interesting, attracting kind of color...  [The] back-story to purple is that it inspires confidence in your creativity, and we're living in a world where that kind of creative innovation is greatly admired. In the world of color, purple is an attention-getter, and it has a meaning. It speaks to people, and we felt that it was time for the purple family to be celebrated.  That's why we chose the particular shade called Radiant Orchid. | [[Leatrice Eiseman]]<ref>{{cite web| last= Eiseman | first = Leatrice |title= Lee Eiseman, Executive Director, Pantone Color Institute | url= http://www.signazon.com/spotlight-lee-eiseman-part-1.aspx |work= Spotlight |publisher = Signazon |accessdate= 24 January 2014}}</ref>|source=}}

Pantone has said that color "has always been an integral part of how a culture expresses the attitudes and emotions of the times."<ref name="Celebrate Color">{{cite web|title=Celebrate Color.|url=http://www.pantone.com/pages/pantone.aspx?pg=21111&ca=90|website=pantone.com|publisher=Panton|accessdate=7 December 2014}}</ref>

==Intellectual property==
Pantone asserts that their lists of color numbers and pigment values are the [[intellectual property]] of Pantone and free use of the list is not allowed.<ref name = termuse>{{Citation | contribution-url = http://www.pantone.com/pages/pantone/pantone.aspx?pg=19309&ca=10 | publisher = Pantone | title = Terms of Use | section = Clause 4 | quote = published materials of Pantone, are protected by copyright laws and include, for example, graphic presentations, color references, Pantone Colors, Pantone Names, numbers, formulas, and software |date = 30 July 2009}}.</ref> This is frequently held as a reason Pantone colors cannot be supported in [[open-source software]] and are not often found in low-cost proprietary software.<ref name=Linux/>  Pantone has been accused of "being intentionally unclear" about its exact legal claims, but it is acknowledged that "the simplest claim would be trademark misappropriation or dilution towards someone who produced a color palette marketed as compatible with Pantone's".<ref name=Linux>{{Cite web|url=http://archive09.linux.com/feature/49236|title=Pantone and free software|website=Linux.com {{!}} The source for Linux information|language=en|access-date=2017-08-17}}</ref>  Pantone palettes supplied by printer manufacturers can be obtained freely, and usually do not come with usage restrictions beyond a sales ban on hard copies of the palette.

